<h1 id="introduction">Introduction</h1>

<h2 id="contributions">Contributions</h2>

<p>The paper proposes a black-box optimization system and targets the following property.</p>

<ol>
  <li>ease to use: low code, less config, and setup.</li>
  <li>integrate state-of-art existing algorithms</li>
  <li><strong>high availability.</strong></li>
  <li>high scalability:
    <ul>
      <li>Millions of trails per the study</li>
      <li><strong>Thousands of parallel trails per study</strong></li>
      <li>billions of studies.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<h1 id="the-system">The system</h1>

<h2 id="definition">Definition</h2>

<p>A trail:  A trail is one list of parameters, and this parameter will have a result f(x). The trail can be complete or pending.</p>

<p>A study: single optimization run over many trails. f(x) does not change during a study.</p>

<p><img src="https://github.com/NLGithubWP/tech-notebook/raw/master/img/a_img_store/image-20220511183150871.png" alt="image-20220511183150871" /></p>

<h2 id="algorithms">Algorithms</h2>

<p>Studies with &lt; 1k trails, use batched Gaussian process bandits and expected improvement acquisition function</p>

<p>Studies with &gt; 10K trails, use randomSearch/ gridSearch.</p>

<h2 id="automated-early-stopping">Automated early stopping</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Performance Curve Stopping Rule:</p>

    <p>performs regression on the performance curves to make a prediction of the final objective value of a Trial given a set of Trials that are already Completed,</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Median Stopping Rule:</p>

    <p>if the trial‚Äôs best objective value by step ùë† is strictly worse than the median value of the running averages</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<h2 id="transfer-learning">Transfer learning</h2>

<p>Tune the hyperparameter of the same model on a new dataset based on the picked hyperparameter of the same model on the previous dataset.</p>

<p>For instance, one might tune the learning rate and regularization of a machine learning system, then use that Study as a prior to tuning the same ML system on a different data set.</p>

